Url.Title: Introducing Saleslogix for Web
Url.Abstract: Introducing Saleslogix for Web Saleslogix manages all aspects of the sales cycle over the Web. In addition to tracking contacts, accounts, leads, opportunities, tickets and activities, users have access to tools for automating processes, and creating e-mails, faxes, and letters using mail merge. With additional security permissions, you may also have access to administrative tools for user, team, department, and pick list management.

Url.Title: Using the Help System
Url.Abstract: Using the Help System The Help systems available with Saleslogix contain explanations of features and functionality, with links to related subjects.

Url.Title: Assumptions and Conventions
Url.Abstract: Assumptions and Conventions This online guide assumes that you have a working knowledge of your browser (for example, using a search engine or entering a URL) and fundamental operating system concepts (for example, clicking and dragging, file navigation, and so on). If you are unfamiliar with these concepts, see the Help files available for your browser.

Url.Title: New User Tips
Url.Abstract: New User Tips If this is your first time using the Saleslogix Web Client or Saleslogix Customer Portal, keep the following tips in mind:

Url.Title: Getting Started with the Saleslogix Web Client
Url.Abstract: Getting Started with the Saleslogix Web Client The Saleslogix Web Client helps you manage all aspects of the sales cycle over the Web. This topic includes links to commonly performed tasks and overview topics to help you begin to use the Saleslogix Web Client.

Url.Title: Logging on to Saleslogix
Url.Abstract: Logging on to the Saleslogix Web Client Before you begin, locate your User ID and password. If you do not have this information, contact your system administrator.

Url.Title: Editing User Options
Url.Abstract: Editing User Options Saleslogix provides tools to allow you to modify some parts of the interface so that you can work in the way that suits you best. User Options allow you to set specific preferences for such features as the view that appears when you start the Saleslogix Web Client and Alerts. Your settings that you enter are recorded for you and are not visible to other Saleslogix users. Some options are shared between the Saleslogix Client and Saleslogix Web Client.

Url.Title: Related Documentation
Url.Abstract: Related Documentation In addition to this Help system, the following printed and online documentation is available:

Url.Title: Understanding Your Workspace
Url.Abstract: The workspace is the area where various views appear in the main Saleslogix Web Client. Related Topics

Url.Title: Managing Resources
Url.Abstract: Managing Resources You can add a resource, such as a conference room, to the list of available resources that appears when you schedule an activity.

Url.Title: Using the Resource Detail view
Url.Abstract: Using the Resource Detail view Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record.

Url.Title: Managing Qualifications
Url.Abstract: Managing Qualifications Qualifications are a collection of qualification items that are used to validate lead information or determine if and when a lead is ready to become a sales opportunity.

Url.Title: Using the Qualification Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Qualification Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record.

Url.Title: A New Employee Needs Access to SalesLogix
Url.Abstract: A New Employee Needs Access to Saleslogix When someone requires access to Saleslogix, use this checklist to ensure you complete all steps to add the new user. (You may find it helpful to print a copy of this checklist as well as some of the linked topics containing additional information.)

Url.Title: A User Leaves or No Longer Requires SalesLogix
Url.Abstract: A User Leaves or No Longer Requires Saleslogix When a user leaves your company, it is best to convert his or her user profile to a retired user rather than delete it. Retired users do not use a license and cannot log on, but their name is preserved in the database. This prevents history records from displaying “Unknown User.” Use the following checklist when a user leaves.

Url.Title: A User Takes Extended Leave
Url.Abstract: A User Takes Extended Leave When a user takes an extended leave, use this checklist to ensure the user’s accounts and activities are handled correctly.

Url.Title: A User Returns From Extended Leave
Url.Abstract: A User Returns From Extended Leave When a user returns from an extended leave, use this checklist to reverse the actions you completed following the User Takes Extended Leave checklist.

Url.Title: User Detail View
Url.Abstract: User Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Understanding Users
Url.Abstract: Understanding Users Users are the people that can access your Saleslogix database. Each user has a profile that defines information such as the user name, title, manager, team membership, department membership, and security access.

Url.Title: Using the Users List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Users List View The Users List view displays Saleslogix users in a grid. The grid provides information about each user, such as the user's title and the user type.

Url.Title: Adding a User
Url.Abstract: Adding a User Before you add one or more users, review A New Employee Needs Access to Saleslogix and complete the first four check boxes.

Url.Title: Activating or Deactivating a User Login
Url.Abstract: Activating or Deactivating a User Login You can set the login status of a user as active or inactive. New users are active by default. When a user login is inactive, they cannot access the Saleslogix database. However, an inactive user’s profile is not deleted and a license remains assigned to that user.

Url.Title: Changing a User's Profile
Url.Abstract: Changing a User's Profile Users cannot be converted to a user template and user templates cannot be converted to other user types.

Url.Title: Changing Other Users' Passwords - Admin
Url.Abstract: Changing a Password (Administrator) You can change a user's password in the Users view and through user Options.

Url.Title: Other Calendars Tab
Url.Abstract: Other Calendars Tab Use the Other Calendars tab on the User Detail view to set permission rights for a user to view and modify other user’s calendars. By default, users do not have access to any other user’s calendars. When a user's calendar is added to another user's profile, view access rights are automatically enabled.

Url.Title: Working with Teams
Url.Abstract: Working with Teams Teams can consist of users, departments, and other teams. You might create teams based on region, territory, type of account, or department.

Url.Title: Creating a Team
Url.Abstract: Creating a Team A team can consist of users, teams, and departments. When creating a team, you must select one person as the team owner.

Url.Title: Adding Team Members
Url.Abstract: Adding Team Members You can add users, departments, or another team to a team. You can add team members one member at a time or in a group. When you add a user to a team, you can automatically include the user's immediate manager. However, there is no further inheritance (for example, the manager's manager). Tell me more about team security...

Url.Title: Removing or Replacing Team Members
Url.Abstract: Removing or Replacing Team Members You can remove team members or replace one user with another on a team.

Url.Title: Creating a Department
Url.Abstract: Creating a Department A department is a specialized team. By default, users are not assigned to a department.

Url.Title: Pick List Detail View
Url.Abstract: Pick List Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: What are Pick Lists?
Url.Abstract: What are Pick Lists? A pick list is a list of values that you can select from when entering data in a field. For example, in a City field, the user can select from a list of cities rather than typing in a value. Tell me more...

Url.Title: Adding a Pick List
Url.Abstract: Adding a Pick List To add Related Topics

Url.Title: Managing Items in a Pick List
Url.Abstract: Managing Items in a Pick List You can edit a pick list by adding a new item, editing an existing item, or deleting an item from the pick list.

Url.Title: Job Manager List View
Url.Abstract: Job Manager List View The Job Manager provides a user interface for creating and managing the jobs sent to the Saleslogix Job Server. Job Server is an engine for processing single and\or recurring tasks for immediate or delayed execution. The Job Server is a shared service that can be consumed by any Saleslogix client, including Web, Windows, and Mobile. There are 9 threads to the Job Server, enabling multiple jobs to run at one time.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Role Detail View
Url.Abstract: Use the Role Detail view to edit, view or delete a role.

Url.Title: What are Roles and Secured Actions?
Url.Abstract: What are Roles and Secured Actions? A role determines what functionality a user can access in the Web Client. Roles use secured actions to control access to user interface elements such as pages, menus, menu items, toolbars, and buttons. When you control access to individual user interface elements, you can control access to actions such as editing, deleting, or printing. Current secured elements are all user interface elements giving access to accounts, contacts, and opportunities.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Creating a Role
Url.Abstract: Creating Saleslogix user roles to grant permissions to features and functionality in the Web Client.

Url.Title: Using Integrations
Url.Abstract: Using Integrations Integrations allow communication between Saleslogix and external applications and services. Each integration may communicate different information, or have different communication behavior. Tell me more For example, the Accounting Integration with X3 synchronizes specified accounting information between Saleslogix and X3. Other integrations might have single-direction communication. For example, an integration with a social media service might configure Saleslogix to get information from the service to display it.

Url.Title: Using the SData Sync Configuration View
Url.Abstract: Using the SData Sync Configuration View Use the SData Sync Configuration view to set up the Saleslogix feed used to synchronize Saleslogix with integrated systems.

Url.Title: Using the Integrations List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Integrations List View The Integrations List view displays all of the integrations that you have access to. This list includes all of the integrations released by Saleslogix as well as any custom integrations. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Using the Integration Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Integration Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected integration. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Integrations Links Tab
Url.Abstract: Integrations Links Tab Use the Links tab to view and manage the links that transfer information between Saleslogix and an external system. Depending on the link type, you may see one or multiple links listed on the tab.The Links tab is available only for integrations with a synchronization method of Client-side Sync or Server Sync.

Url.Title: Configuring the Integration Synchronization Service
Url.Abstract: Configuring the Integration Synchronization Service The Integration Synchronization Service (Saleslogix SData Sync Service) allows data transfer between Saleslogix and your integrations. The service must be started and set to run as automatic.

Url.Title: Sync Jobs List View
Url.Abstract: Sync Jobs List View The Sync Jobs List View displays information about synchronization jobs run between Saleslogix and external integrations.

Url.Title: Sync History List View
Url.Abstract: Sync History List View The Sync History List View displays information about synchronization cycles run between Saleslogix and external integrations.

Url.Title: Using Accounting Integration
Url.Abstract: Using Accounting Integration Typically, a Saleslogix user manages the integration of accounts and sales orders from Saleslogix and your accounting system by:

Url.Title: Introducing Accounting Integration
Url.Abstract: Introducing Accounting Integration Accounting Integration allows you to share information between Saleslogix and any accounting system that supports the SData CRM ERP Contract. Saleslogix Web Client users can view open sales orders, customer invoices, customer payments, invoices, and their corresponding details. Users may also create sales orders in the integrated accounting system from within Saleslogix. These sales orders are not integrated with Saleslogix sales orders.

Url.Title: Configuring X3 Accounting Integration
Url.Abstract: Configuring X3 Accounting Integration Complete the following tasks to configure an X3 accounting integration.

Url.Title: Using Check for Duplicates
Url.Abstract: Using Check for Duplicates The Check for Duplicates wizard compares records in Saleslogix to determine if your data contains duplicates. The wizard creates a job containing possible duplicate data. You can use the job results to merge or remove duplicate data.

Url.Title: What Are Contacts?
Url.Abstract: What Are Contacts? Contacts are key people associated with an account. A contact can only belong to one account, however, a contact may be associated with multiple opportunities. Your access to contact information is determined by your access rights to that contact's account. You always have access to your personal contacts.

Url.Title: Using the Contact List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Contact List View The List view displays all of the contacts that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Using the Contact Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Contact Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Adding a Contact
Url.Abstract: Adding Contact and Account Information You can use the Contact/Account Information view to add a new contact and account or to add a new contact to an existing account.

Url.Title: Editing a Contact
Url.Abstract: Editing a Contact Use the Contact Detail view to edit contact information. To undo any changes, click Reset before clicking the Save button.

Url.Title: Deleting a Contact
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Contact When you delete a contact you also delete the contact's history, notes, and any open activities. You can also delete contacts by deleting the contact's account.

Url.Title: Moving a Contact
Url.Abstract: Moving a Contact You can move a contact to another account. This is useful if companies merge and a contact's account changes, or if a contact simply joins another company and wants to maintain a business relationship.You can also use this feature to move a contact that was incorrectly created under the wrong account.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - What Are Accounts?
Url.Abstract: Saleslogix Accounts are your customers which may include one or more contacts. Accounts are owned by an individual user, a team of users, or everyone.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Using the Account List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Account List view in the Saleslogix Web Client. Use groups and lookups to narrow the list of accounts.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Using the Account Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Account Detail view in the Saleslogix Web Client. Use the Account Detail view to edit, view or delete an account.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Adding a New Account
Url.Abstract: Adding new accounts in the Saleslogix Web Client. On the New menu, click Account. Complete the account information.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Editing an Account
Url.Abstract: Editing account information in the Saleslogix Web Client. Open the Account Detail view, make your changes, and click the Save button.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Deleting an Account
Url.Abstract: Deleting an account from the Saleslogix Web Client. Open the account's detail view, click the Delete button.

Url.Title: Linking Records with an Accounting System
Url.Abstract: Linking Records with an Accounting System When you promote an account, you are linking a Saleslogix account with your accounting system.

Url.Title: What Are Opportunities?
Url.Abstract: What Are Opportunities? Your potential sales to accounts and contacts are called opportunities. Opportunities allow you to collect and report on a variety of information relating to an opportunity, such as probability of closing a sale, estimated close dates, and more. You can track any combination of the following opportunity-related information.

Url.Title: Using the Opportunity List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Opportunity List View The List view displays all of the contacts that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Using the Opportunity Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Opportunity Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Adding a New Opportunity
Url.Abstract: Adding a New Opportunity Use the Insert Opportunity view to enter opportunity information and to add, edit, or remove products, competitors, or contacts. You can also update the opportunity currency and rate if you have Multi-Currency enabled.

Url.Title: Editing an Opportunity
Url.Abstract: Editing an Opportunity Use the Opportunity Detail view to edit opportunity information. To edit an opportunity

Url.Title: Closing an Opportunity
Url.Abstract: Closing an Opportunity When you are ready to close an opportunity, you can change the status of the opportunity in the Opportunity Detail view to Closed-Won or Closed-Lost. It is recommended that you close an opportunity even if it is not a sale. For future reference, you should provide the reason for closing the opportunity. Use the Opportunity Comments box to provide more information on the reason for the loss or for the won sale.

Url.Title: Deleting an Opportunity
Url.Abstract: Deleting an Opportunity To delete an opportunity Related Topics

Url.Title: What are Sales Orders?
Url.Abstract: What Are Sales Orders? Sales Orders track the products purchased by your accounts. Sales orders include information such as, the date the sales order was made, the date the sales order was promised to the customer and its status.

Url.Title: Using the Sales Order List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Sales Order List View The Sales Orders List view displays all the sales orders that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Using the Sales Order Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Sales Order Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Adding a Sales Order
Url.Abstract: Adding a Sales Order Use this view to add a sales order, including the billing address, shipping address or product information and other sales order information.

Url.Title: Editing a Sales Order
Url.Abstract: Editing a Sales Order Use the Sales Order Detail view to edit sales order information. To undo any changes, click Reset before clicking the Save button.

Url.Title: Copying a Sales Order
Url.Abstract: Copying a Sales Order You can copy sales order information such as, account, billing, shipping and product information.

Url.Title: Using Widgets
Url.Abstract: Using Widgets Saleslogix provides several out-of-the-box widgets. You can add, edit, and remove widgets from the dashboard, and you can rearrange widgets on the page with drag-and-drop.

Url.Title: Introducing Dashboards
Url.Abstract: The Dashboard allows you to display and interact with a variety of performance and analysis tools on the Welcome page of the Saleslogix Web Client. You can maintain one or more personalized dashboard tabs and, with the appropriate permissions, you can modify dashboards provided by Saleslogix or customized by your administrator.

Url.Title: Working with Dashboards
Url.Abstract: Working with Dashboards Dashboards display as tabs on the Welcome page and contain customizable, pre-defined analytics in the form of charting and list widgets. The Welcome page can contain multiple dashboard instances and each dashboard can contain multiple widgets.

Url.Title: Introducing Widgets
Url.Abstract: Introducing Widgets Widgets are plug-ins you can add to a dashboard. There are several types of widgets you can use to display your data. Move your mouse over the chart in a widget to display the dimension and metric selected for that widget.

Url.Title: Customer Service Overview
Url.Abstract: Customer Service Overview The Customer Service and Support features allow designated users to track, qualify, and resolve customer questions and issues. With these features, users can better analyze customer service issues to improve customer satisfaction.

Url.Title: What are Tickets?
Url.Abstract: Tickets are records of customer inquiries or complaints. They can contain the information necessary to report, investigate, and close an inquiry or problem. You can insert new tickets for an account or contact, track your time spent resolving issues for a ticket against a contract by using the Punch In/Punch Out button record calendar and other activities for a ticket, and search for existing tickets using the Lookup. In addition, you can use SpeedSearch to search for existing problems and their resolutions that may apply to the ticket's issue.

Url.Title: Using the Ticket List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Ticket List View The List view displays all of the tickets that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Adding a Ticket
Url.Abstract: Adding a New Ticket Use the Insert New Ticket view to add a new ticket for a new inquiry or problem for an account. Before you add a ticket, the account and contact must already exist in Saleslogix.

Url.Title: Using the Ticket Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Ticket Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Editing or Closing a Ticket
Url.Abstract: Editing or Closing a Ticket When you need to change the status of a ticket, or make changes to a ticket's information, use the Ticket Detail view. To undo any changes, click Reset before clicking the Save button.

Url.Title: Deleting a Ticket
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Ticket Your security access determines what functions are available. Contact your administrator for any access rights changes. WebViewer users may not access full functionality.

Url.Title: What are Contracts?
Url.Abstract: What are Contracts? Contracts are agreements that detail specific support after the sale of a product. A Warranty, for example, can become a contract to support a specific asset after the sale.

Url.Title: Using the Contract List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Contract List View The Contract List view displays all of the contracts that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Using the Contract Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Contract Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Adding a Contract
Url.Abstract: Adding a Contract Use the Insert New Contract view to create a contract record. Use the copy button to quickly create a new record with similar information.

Url.Title: Making a Contract Inactive
Url.Abstract: Making a Contract Inactive You can make a contract inactive when no tickets are associated with it. Inactive contracts will still appear in the Account Service Information dialog box.

Url.Title: Contract Types
Url.Abstract: The five default contract types are: Related Topics

Url.Title: What are Defects?
Url.Abstract: A defect is a record describing a problem in a product or process. It is similar to a ticket, but people involved in the design or construction of the product typically resolve defects. The system tracks defects so that problems with a product or process can be resolved in a timely manner, and company management is aware of issues with these products or processes.

Url.Title: Using the Defect List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Defect List View The Defect List view displays all of the defects that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Using the Defect Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Defect Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Adding a Defect
Url.Abstract: Adding a Defect Use the Insert New Defect view to create a defect record. Use the copy button to quickly create a new record with similar information.

Url.Title: Closing a Defect
Url.Abstract: Closing a Defect The stage at which a defect is closed and the person responsible for closing the defect depend on the process within your company.

Url.Title: Working with Returns
Url.Abstract: Working with Returns Returns are agreements to accept returned products from a customer for service, replacement, refund, or credit You can use the Return Detail view to work with a single return, or the Returns List view to work with returns in a spreadsheet-type format.

Url.Title: Using the Return List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Return List View The Return List view displays all of the returns that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Using the Return Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Return Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Adding a Return
Url.Abstract: Adding a Return Use the Insert Return view to create a return record. To add a return Related Topics

Url.Title: Closing a Return
Url.Abstract: Closing a Return The stage at which a return is closed and the person responsible for closing the return depend on the process within your company. As an example, when the product has been returned by the customer and the replacement product has been shipped, that might be the stage at which you would close a return.

Url.Title: What Are Assets?
Url.Abstract: What Are Assets? Assets are products that have been sold to your customers. They are the physical products the customer owns which may or may not be serialized.

Url.Title: Adding an Account Asset
Url.Abstract: Adding or Editing an Account Asset You can add a new asset to an account or edit the list of assets associated with an account.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - What Are Activities and Events?
Url.Abstract: Saleslogix Activities include phone calls, meetings and to-dos such as sending correspondence or preparing presentations. Events are trade shows, business trips, conferences or other occasions that may span several days.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Scheduling or Editing a Activity
Url.Abstract: Scheduling or editing activities in the Saleslogix Web Client.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Completing an Activity
Url.Abstract: Completing an activity in the Saleslogix Web Client creates a history record in the Notes/History tab for the related account, contact, lead, ticket or opportunity.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Completing an Activity from the Menu
Url.Abstract: Completing an activity from the Saleslogix Web Client Scheule menu allows you to complete a scheduled or unscheduled activity which creates a history record in the Notes/History tab for the related account, contact, lead, ticket or opportunity.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Completing Multiple Activities
Url.Abstract: Completing multiple activities at one time in the Saleslogix Web Client creates a separate history record for each activity in the Notes/History tab for the related account, contact, lead, ticket or opportunity.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Deleting an Activity
Url.Abstract: Deleting activities in the Saleslogix Web Client. If an activity is cancelled or was entered in error, it should be deleted to remove it from your calendar.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Web Client Help - Scheduling or Editing a Event
Url.Abstract: Scheduling or editing events in the Saleslogix Web Client. Events are trade shows, business trips, conferences or other occasions that appear on your calendar and may span several days.

Url.Title: Calendar Options
Url.Abstract: Setting Calendar Options Use the Calendar tab to set the default options for your calendar. Calendar Options allow you to adjust the content and appearance of your calendar to accommodate the way you work. You can set the type of information that displays in activities, the start and end of the work day, the default calendar view, default interval on the calendar, and whether or not completed activities (history) items display. History items only display on the day and week calendars by default.

Url.Title: Activity Calendar
Url.Abstract: Using the Calendar Use the Calendar to manage your time and keep track of scheduled activities and events. The Saleslogix Calendar displays both open and completed activities and events, depending on your calendar options. You can view your schedule by the day, week, or month view. Use the calendar right-click menu to schedule, edit, complete, or delete activities and events.

Url.Title: What Are Contact Processes?
Url.Abstract: What Are Contact Processes? A process is a series of tasks that are executed in a specific sequence over a period of time. Use Contact Processes to automate repetitive tasks and provide a consistent, automated way of following up with customers. Contact Processes are created using the Architect.

Url.Title: Process Manager
Url.Abstract: Using the Process Manager The Contact Process Manager on the Web allows you to view the processes assigned to your contacts or add new processes. Any further changes to processes must be done in the Saleslogix Network Client or Saleslogix Remote Client. Use the Processes tab in the Contact Detail view to view processes attached to a single contact.

Url.Title: Scheduling a Process
Url.Abstract: Scheduling a Process To schedule a process Related Topics

Url.Title: What are Sales Processes?
Url.Abstract: What are Sales Processes? Sales processes help you to manage your sales pipeline. A sales process shows you the steps to complete as you work to make a sale. It can prompt you to complete activities, such as making phone calls and writing letters. You can attach a sales process to an open opportunity by selecting from a list of available processes. For example, you can select a sales process called "Large Deals" for an opportunity with large potential revenue.

Url.Title: Updating Sales Process Stages
Url.Abstract: Updating Sales Process Stages You can update the stages in a Sales Process. You can complete a stage even if you have not completed all of the stage steps. You can also change the current stage.

Url.Title: Finding Sales Processes
Url.Abstract: Finding Sales Processes Sales processes help you to manage your sales pipeline. You can attach a sales process to an open opportunity by selecting from a list of available processes.

Url.Title: What are Leads?
Url.Abstract: What are Leads? Leads are unqualified potential customers. Use lead qualification criteria to determine if a lead has valid information, already exists as a lead or contact, or is ready to be converted to a sales opportunity. Once qualified, a lead can be converted to or merged with a contact and account. You can also create a new sales opportunity.

Url.Title: Using the Lead List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Lead List View The Lead List view displays all the leads that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Using the Lead Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Lead Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Adding a Lead
Url.Abstract: Adding a Lead Use the Insert Lead dialog box to add a new lead to the Saleslogix Web Client. To add Related Topics

Url.Title: Importing Leads from a List
Url.Abstract: Importing Leads from a List Use the Import Leads view to import lists of leads into Saleslogix. You may only import leads from a comma-separated-values (CSV) list. Valid file types include Microsoft Excel, .txt files, and other database file types, but files must be saved as a CSV file.

Url.Title: Qualifying Leads | Saleslogix Web Client Help
Url.Abstract: Qualifying a Lead A lead may contain unqualified information. You can use lead qualification criteria to validate information and determine if the lead is a sales opportunity. Once qualified, you can convert a lead to a contact and account and create a new sales opportunity.

Url.Title: Deleting Leads
Url.Abstract: Deleting Leads Deleting a lead also deletes all information associated with the lead. To delete a lead

Url.Title: Adding a Campaign
Url.Abstract: Adding a Campaign Use the Insert Campaign view to add campaign information. After adding a campaign you can add products, stages and tasks, and targets.

Url.Title: Deleting a Campaign
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Campaign When you delete a campaign, you also delete all of the information associated with that campaign, including response and opportunity information.

Url.Title: Copying a Campaign
Launching a Campaign
Url.Abstract: Launching a Campaign When a campaign is launched, the campaign target contacts and leads are assigned to the first stage of a campaign and their status is changed to "Launched".

Url.Title: Using the Campaign Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Campaign Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Using the Campaign List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Campaign List View The List view displays all of the campaigns that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: What are Campaign Targets?
Url.Abstract: What are Campaign Targets? Targets are the contacts and leads that will be contacted as part of a campaign. You can segment the market in order to create a suitable list of campaign targets that fits within your budget.

Url.Title: Managing Campaign Targets
Url.Abstract: Managing Campaign Targets Use the Lookup Targets dialog box to determine which contacts and leads should be targeted for a campaign.

Url.Title: Campaign Stages and Tasks Tab
Url.Abstract: Campaign Stages/Tasks Tab The Campaign Stages/Tasks tab lists all of the stages and tasks associated with a campaign.

Url.Title: Adding/Editing/Completing Campaign Stages
Url.Abstract: Adding/Editing/Completing Campaign Stages Campaign stages are groups of tasks that can help Saleslogix Marketing users manage their campaigns. You can add and edit stage information, or complete a stage once it is finished.

Url.Title: Adding/Editing/Completing Campaign Tasks
Url.Abstract: Adding/Editing/Completing Campaign Tasks Campaign tasks can help Saleslogix Marketing users manage their campaigns. You can add and edit task information, or complete a task once it is finished.

Url.Title: Using Mail Merge
Url.Abstract: Using Mail Merge You can use Mail Merge when you need to correspond with a group of contacts, accounts, opportunities, or leads. Mail Merge helps you simplify the process of sending the same information to numerous people by merging information into a template. You can merge to a file, send an e-mail, send a fax, or print the merged document.

Url.Title: Templates Overview
Url.Abstract: Templates Overview You can use templates to create letters, proposals, faxes, or e-mail messages that will be used for more than one contact or lead. Templates use standard text that does not change, as well as mail merge fields that use Saleslogix information that changes depending upon the contact or lead being merged.

Url.Title: About the Write Menu
Url.Abstract: Using the Write Menu You can use the Saleslogix Write menu to perform a mail merge or to send an e-mail. You can communicate with a single contact or lead or with a group of contacts or leads.

Url.Title: Writing and Sending an E-mail Message
Url.Abstract: Writing and Sending an E-mail Message You can write an e-mail to a single contact or lead using either the Write E-mail or the Write E-mail Using Template option. If you need to send an e-mail message to more than one contact or lead, use Mail Merge.

Url.Title: Writing and Sending a Fax Message
Url.Abstract: Writing and Sending a Fax Message The following describes how to write and send a fax to a single contact or lead. If you need to send a fax to more than one contact or lead, use Mail Merge.

Url.Title: Writing and Sending Letters or Memos
Url.Abstract: Writing and Sending Letters or Memos The following describes how to write a letter to a single contact or lead. If you need to send a letter or memo to more than one contact or lead, use Mail Merge.

Url.Title: Printing Address Labels or Envelopes
Url.Abstract: Printing Address Labels or Envelopes You can use Mail Merge to create and print address labels and envelopes. You can create address labels or envelopes for one contact or lead or for multiple contacts or leads.

Url.Title: Viewing Invalid or Failed Merge Information
Url.Abstract: Viewing Invalid or Failed Merge Information Saleslogix Mail Merge provides two forms of information when invalid or failed merges occur:

Url.Title: What are Reports?
Url.Abstract: What are Reports? The Reports List view provides a list of pre-defined sample reports to enable you to view and analyze information in the Saleslogix database. You can run reports related to Main views such as Contact, Account, Opportunity and so on. If you prefer, you can modify the report to accommodate your business needs. The specific reports available to you are determined by your system administrator.

Url.Title: Report Preview
Url.Abstract: Report Preview You can only see reports that have been released to you or to a team that you belong to. You cannot save reports in the Saleslogix Web Client.

Url.Title: Running a Report
Url.Abstract: Running a Report Reports enable you to view information about contacts, accounts, opportunities, tickets, and other related data.

Url.Title: SpeedSearch
Url.Abstract: SpeedSearch SpeedSearch is a powerful tool that helps you find information stored in the Saleslogix database or external files. For example, you can search through existing tickets or procedures to help solve a customer's problem, or search for a specific document, like a sales presentation. The type of information you can search for depends on the indexes your system administrator has set up in the Administrator.

Url.Title: Using SpeedSearch from the Menu Bar
Url.Abstract: Using SpeedSearch from the Menu Bar You can now enter your search criteria and perform a SpeedSearch from the Menu Bar.

Url.Title: Searching for Information
Url.Abstract: Searching for Information Use SpeedSearch to set up your search criteria and start a search. How you set up the search criteria determines how and where SpeedSearch locates items matching the keywords you enter.

Url.Title: What Are Groups?
Url.Abstract: What are Groups? Groups are a collection of records. Groups can help you manage your workflow. You can use groups to work with a subset of records, select data to send mailings, e-mails, and faxes using the Mail Merge feature. A record can be in more than one group. You can export group records to Excel or share your groups with other users.

Url.Title: Saving a Lookup as a Group
Url.Abstract: Saving a Lookup as a Group After you create a lookup to find contacts, accounts, opportunities, leads or tickets, you may want to save the lookup as a group so you can access it again.

Url.Title: Adding an Ad Hoc Group
Url.Abstract: Adding an Ad Hoc Group You can create an ad hoc group to store a list of selected records from any of the List views.

Url.Title: Modifying Groups
Url.Abstract: Modifying Groups You can use Query Builder to modify your groups. To modify a group The Query Builder opens.

Url.Title: Sharing Templates with Other Users
Url.Abstract: Sharing Templates with Other Users You can share your templates with other Saleslogix users, teams, or departments.

Url.Title: Exporting a Group to Excel
Url.Abstract: Exporting a Group to Excel You can export groups to Excel. The group column headings and formatting will also be exported.

Url.Title: Creating an Advanced Query
Url.Abstract: Use Query Builder to create a group. Advanced queries allow you to set the conditions for the group. Each time you open the group, the query evaluates the database to determine which records to display. If you want to ensure the group does not change, create an ad hoc group instead.

Url.Title: Using Query Builder
Url.Abstract: Query Builder enables you to select data from the database based on one or more conditions. For example, you may need to see a list of primary contacts in the banking industry. Query Builder is connected to various areas throughout the Saleslogix clients. To use Query Builder effectively, you must understand the Saleslogix database structure and relational database concepts, such as data relationships and joins.

Url.Title: Opening Query Builder
Url.Abstract: Opening Query Builder You can use Query Builder to add or edit groups. To open Query Builder Related Topics

Url.Title: View the SQL Version of a Query
Url.Abstract: Viewing the SQL Version of a Query When you create a query, it is converted to a SQL (Structured Query Language) statement. This statement is applied against the database. You can view the SQL version of a query, but you cannot modify the SQL statement.

Url.Title: Query Builder Properties
Url.Abstract: Query Builder Properties Use the Query Builder Properties tab to enter the name and purpose of a query.

Url.Title: Query Builder Conditions
Url.Abstract: Query Builder Conditions Use the Query Builder Conditions tab to add, edit, or delete conditional statements that are applied against the database to select data. Conditions are applied in the order they appear in the grid; however, you can use the Move Up and Move Down buttons to change the order. You can also group the conditional statements.

Url.Title: Query Builder Layout
Url.Abstract: Query Builder Layout Use the Query Builder Layout tab to specify which fields are displayed and how the data appears. You can add, edit, delete, or reorder the fields in the layout. You can also set the column name, width, and format of each field. The Layout tab must include at least one field or no data will appear.

Url.Title: Query Builder Sorting
Url.Abstract: Query Builder Sorting Use the Query Builder Sorting tab to specify which field(s) to sort the data by and whether the data appears in ascending or descending order. The sorting criteria are applied in the order in which they appear on the tab.

Url.Title: Query Builder Defaults
Url.Abstract: Query Builder Defaults Use the Query Builder Defaults tab to select only distinct records. Distinct records are records that are not the same or are not duplicate records.

Url.Title: Joining Tables
Url.Abstract: Joining Tables The connection between two tables is called a join and is established using a field that exists in both tables. This field may have a different name in each table but contains the same information. There are two kinds of joins - Local and Global.

Url.Title: Guidelines for Using Joins
Url.Abstract: Guidelines for Using Joins Use the following guidelines when creating table joins in Saleslogix: Related Topics

Url.Title: Global Join Manager
Url.Abstract: Global Join Manager The Global Join Manager displays all global joins in your Saleslogix database, and permits the system administrator or administrative user to add, edit, and delete global joins as necessary. A global join is permanent and exists from session to session in the Query Builder data tree structure.

Url.Title: Using Calculated Fields
Url.Abstract: Using Calculated Fields A calculated field is dynamic and consists of two or more fields from the database. The fields used to create a calculated field can come from one table or from several joined tables. The values that appear for a calculated field are updated after changes are made to the fields comprising it. A calculated field can perform mathematical operations or concatenate strings, depending on the type of calculation.

Url.Title: Adding or Editing a Calculated Field
Url.Abstract: Adding and Editing Calculated Fields To open the Manage Calculated Fields dialog box Related Topics

Url.Title: Delete a Calculated Field
Url.Abstract: Deleting Calculated Fields You can only open the Manage Calculated Fields dialog box if you are logged on as an administrator.

Url.Abstract: Saleslogix and Outlook There are several ways that Saleslogix integrates with Outlook. Before you can use Outlook sync or Outlook Integration, you must configure Outlook Sync and Outlook Integration options in Outlook.

Url.Title: Configuring Outlook Sync and Outlook Integration
Url.Abstract: Configuring Outlook Sync and Outlook Integration Synchronization and integration preferences should be configured in Microsoft Outlook.

Url.Abstract: Setting Saleslogix Connector Connection Options Use the Connection options to set up your connection to the Saleslogix server.

Url.Abstract: Setting Saleslogix Connector Sync Options The Sync options determine what and how information will synchronize between Saleslogix and Outlook.

Url.Title: Setting Saleslogix Connector Address Book Options
Url.Abstract: Setting Saleslogix Connector Address Book Options Use the Address Book options to set up your Saleslogix address book appearance.

Url.Title: Setting Saleslogix Connector Send SLX/Record to History Options
Url.Abstract: Setting Saleslogix Connector Send SLX/Record to History Options Use the Send SLX/Record to History to set e-mail history and attachment options.

Url.Title: Setting Saleslogix Connector Logging Options
Url.Abstract: Setting Saleslogix Connector Logging Options Use the Logging tab to enable logging or view logging information if you are experiencing synchronization problems or are instructed to do so by your administrator.

Url.Abstract: Understanding Contact Synchronization with Outlook Synchronizing contacts between Saleslogix and a Outlook enables you to change a contact record in either application and have the change reflected in both applications. Url.Abstract: Selecting Saleslogix Contacts to Synchronize with Outlook By adding contacts to your contact sync group any changes you make to those contacts are synchronized between Saleslogix and Outlook, based on your sync settings. By removing contacts from the contact sync group, you will stop synchronizing the contact and delete the contact from Outlook. Url.Abstract: Adding Outlook Contacts to Saleslogix To add Outlook contacts to Saleslogix, you must first create and configure a contact sync group in Saleslogix and set your contact sync options.

Url.Abstract: Understanding Calendar Synchronization with Outlook Calendar integration allows you to synchronize your calendar between Saleslogix and Outlook. Your administrator must configure and grant permission before you can synchronize calendars with Outlook.
