Url.Abstract: Literature Item Information Boxes The following table describes the default information boxes.

Url.Title: Using the Literature Items List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Literature Items List View The List view displays all of the literature items that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Literature Requests Tab
Url.Abstract: Literature Requests Tab The Literature Requests tab displays on the Account and Contact Detail Views, and lists all literature requests for the account or contact. The Literature Requests Tab contains the request date, send date, and what the request is regarding.

Url.Title: Scheduling a Literature Request
Url.Abstract: You can schedule a literature request to have marketing materials or other documents sent to one or more contacts. After you schedule a request, the person or group at your company responsible for literature fulfillment can fulfill and complete the request.

Url.Title: Delete Literature Requests
Url.Abstract: Delete a Literature Request You can delete literature requests from the Activities view, or from the Literature Requests view.

Url.Title: Fulfilling, Completing or Rejecting Literature Requests
Url.Abstract: Fulfilling, Completing or Rejecting Literature Requests Use the Literature Request List view Common Tasks to fulfill, complete or reject literature requests.

Url.Title: Literature Request Detail View
Url.Abstract: Literature Request Detail View Use the Literature Request Detail view to see in-depth information about a specific order for literature to be sent to a contact. More than one literature request can exist for a particular contact. The Literature Request Detail view by default includes the names of the user who scheduled the request, the date by which it should be filled, a brief description, the contact and related account names, total cost, delivery method, priority, current status, fulfillment date, and user who fulfilled the request. Literature requests cannot be edited.

Url.Title: Managing Literature Requests
Url.Abstract: Managing Literature Requests Use the Literature Requests list view to view, fulfill, complete or reject literature requests.

Url.Title: Finding Records
Url.Abstract: Finding Records You can find a record by choosing criteria from a pick list and entering text. To find records

Url.Title: Using Lookup
Url.Abstract: Using Lookup To perform a lookup All searches are run on the records you can access. Depending on the options chosen by your administrator, you may also be able to find records based on the group to which it belongs.

Url.Title: Adding or Removing E-mail Attachments
Url.Abstract: About E-mail Attachments You can attach a file when sending an e-mail message to a contact or lead. If the correct options are selected, the file is stored on the Attachments tab for the Contact and Account or Lead, as well as in the default Documents folder. For Saleslogix Web users, the file is stored in the Documents folder of the Web Server. On the Attachments tab, the file name is the exact name of the file or document. In the Documents folder, the file name includes an internal reference code assigned by Saleslogix and the document name.

Url.Title: Attaching a Document to each Contact or Lead Critical Message
Url.Abstract: Attaching a Document to each Contact or Lead Critical Message For Saleslogix Web users, this critical message is applicable if you are merging to a large number of contacts.

Url.Title: Editing Mail Merge Output Prior to Sending
Url.Abstract: Editing Mail Merge Output Prior to Sending You can edit the merged document for individual recipients prior to delivery. For example, you can add a personal greeting to a single letter. This option is found on the Merge Options tab for Mail Merge.

Url.Title: Most Recently Used Templates
Url.Abstract: Most Recently Used Templates You can use the most recently used templates list to select a recently used template without having to open the Select a Template dialog box. The number of recently used templates that appear in the list is set by you or your system administrator when configuring your Saleslogix options.

Url.Title: Selecting the Type of Address
Url.Abstract: Selecting the Type of Address The Select Type of Address dialog box displays when performing a mail merge to a contact with more than one address or a group of contacts and using a template which contains any Saleslogix merge fields from the address table.

Url.Title: Setting Follow-up Activity Date and Time
Url.Abstract: Setting Follow-up Activity Date and Time When using Saleslogix Mail Merge, on the History Options tab, you can schedule a follow-up activity. The activity requires a date and you can specify a time and duration.

Url.Title: Setting History Options for Mail Merge
Url.Abstract: Setting History Options for Mail Merge The History Options tab lets you create a history item for the mail merge and schedule a follow-up activity.

Url.Title: Setting Merge Options for Mail Merge
Url.Abstract: Setting Merge Options for Mail Merge The Merge Options tab lets you set the merge options for Mail Merge.

Url.Title: Viewing Mail Merge Count Information
Url.Abstract: Viewing Mail Merge Count Information Use the Count button to view the possible merge results. The information provides a count and percentage for:

Url.Title: Using the Competitor Detail view
Url.Abstract: Using the Competitor Detail view Use the Detail view to see, add or edit information for a selected record.

Url.Title: Adding a Competitor to the List
Url.Abstract: Adding a Competitor to the List You can add competitors to the competitors list. This list is available to all users when adding or editing opportunity competitors.

Url.Title: Deleting a Competitor from the List
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Competitor from the List You can delete competitors from the list that is available when adding or editing opportunity competitors.

Url.Title: Editing a Competitor in the List
Url.Abstract: Editing a Competitor in the List Use the Competitor Detail view to edit competitor information. To edit

Url.Title: Using the Competitor List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Competitor List View The Competitor List view displays all of the competitors that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Check for Duplicates History List View
Url.Abstract: Check for Duplicates History List View The Check for Duplicates History List view displays all scheduled and completed duplication jobs. To view job results, click the job number in the list.

Url.Title: Check for Duplicates History Detail View
Url.Abstract: Check for Duplicates History Detail View The Check for Duplicates History Detail view displays the details of a job run in the Check for Duplicates Wizard. You can view the job information and resolve any potential duplicates.

Url.Title: Editing or Deleting a Pick List
Url.Abstract: Editing or Deleting a Pick List You can edit a pick list by renaming the pick list, editing the items within the pick list, or deleting the pick list.

Url.Title: Using the Lead Source Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Lead Source Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add or edit information for a selected record.

Url.Title: Adding a Lead Source to the List
Url.Abstract: Adding a Lead Source to the List You can add lead sources, such as trade shows and advertisements, to the list of available lead sources.

Url.Title: Deleting a Lead Source from the List
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Lead Source from the List You can delete lead sources from the list that is available for contact and opportunity lead sources.

Url.Title: Editing a Lead Source in the List
Url.Abstract: Editing a Lead Source in the List Use the Lead Source Detail view to edit lead source information. To edit

Url.Title: Using the Lead Sources List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Lead Sources List View The Lead Sources List view displays all of the lead sources that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Match Options
Url.Abstract: Match Options Use the Match Options dialog box to set advanced filtering criteria for the Check for Duplicates wizard. Options set here apply each time you check for duplicate data.

Url.Title: Adding a Product Package
Url.Abstract: Adding a Product Package You can add packages to the packages list. This list is available when adding or editing opportunity or sales order products.

Url.Title: Deleting a Product Package
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Product Package You can delete product packages from the list that is available when adding or editing opportunity or sales order products and product packages.

Url.Title: Using the Package Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Package Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Editing a Product Package
Url.Abstract: Editing a Product Package Use the Package Detail view to edit package information. To edit Related Topics

Url.Title: Using the Packages List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Packages List View The Packages List view displays all of the packages that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Package Products Tab
Url.Abstract: Package Products Tab Use this view to add, edit, or remove products associated with the package. How Do I?

Url.Title: Using the Pick Lists List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Pick Lists List View The Pick Lists List view displays pick lists in a grid. The grid provides information about each pick list.

Url.Title: Pick List Information Boxes
Url.Abstract: Pick List Information Boxes The following table describes the default information boxes. Tell me more about pick list options...

Url.Title: Items Tab
Url.Abstract: Items Tab Use the Items tab to manage the items in a pick list. This tab displays the items users see when they open a pick list.

Url.Title: Process Duplicate Records Detail View
Url.Abstract: Process Duplicate Records Detail View The Process Duplicate Records Detail view displays the Check for Duplicates job information and any unresolved duplicate records from that job.

Url.Title: Process Duplicate Records List View
Url.Abstract: Process Duplicate Records List View The Process Duplicate Records List view displays all potential duplicates that have been identified by jobs run in the Check for Duplicates Wizard. You can use this view to process the record as a duplicate or not a duplicate.

Url.Title: Using the Product Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Product Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record. The Detail view consists of information boxes, tabs, and a user-defined middle section.

Url.Title: Adding a Product to the List
Url.Abstract: Adding a Product to the List You can add products to the products list. This list is available when adding or editing opportunity or sales order products.

Url.Title: Deleting a Product from the List
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Product from the List You can delete products from the list that is available when adding or editing opportunity or sales order products.

Url.Title: Editing a Product in the List
Url.Abstract: Editing a Product in the List Use the Product Detail view to edit product information.Products are read-only when accounting integration is enabled. You must manage products in your accounting system and synchronize the changes to Saleslogix.

Url.Title: Using the Products List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Products List View The Products List view displays all of the products that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Product Packages Tab
Url.Abstract: Product Packages Tab You can use the Product Packages tab view and manage product packages associated with a product.

Url.Title: Adding or Editing Product Prices
Url.Abstract: Adding or Editing Product Prices You can add or edit product price information. How Do I? Related Topics

Url.Title: Product Price Levels Tab
Url.Abstract: Product Price Levels Tab You can use the Price Levels tab on the Product Detail to view or manage product pricing information.

Url.Title: Resolving Duplicates
Url.Abstract: Resolving Duplicates Each time you run the Check for Duplicates Wizard, a Check for Duplicates History job is created identifying any potential duplicates. Potential duplicates display in the Check for Duplicates History Job Detail view and the Process Duplicates List view. You can use the Check for Duplicates History or Process Duplicates List view to resolve potential duplicates.

Url.Title: Adding/Editing Opportunity Products
Url.Abstract: Adding Products to an Opportunity You can add opportunity products when you create an opportunity or from the Opportunity Detail view Products tab using the Lookup Product dialog box.

Url.Title: Editing Opportunity Product Information
Url.Abstract: Editing Opportunity Product Information Use this dialog box to enter product information such as quantity, price, or discount.

Url.Title: Opportunity Competitors
Url.Abstract: Use this view to add, edit, or remove competitors associated with an opportunity and to help you plan your strategy.

Url.Title: Copying an Opportunity
Url.Abstract: Copying an Opportunity You can copy an existing opportunity to quickly create a new opportunity with the same competitors, contacts, and products as well as other information.

Url.Title: Removing Competitors from an Opportunity
Url.Abstract: Removing a Competitor from an Opportunity You can remove a competitor from an opportunity if that company is no longer competing for the sale, or was selected by mistake. You can delete competitors from the Insert Opportunity dialog box, or the Opportunity Detail view. Deleting a competitor only changes the competitor's association with a particular opportunity. The competitor is not deleted from the database.

Url.Title: Removing Contacts from an Opportunity
Url.Abstract: Removing a Contact from an Opportunity You can remove contacts from an opportunity at any time. You can remove contacts from the Insert Opportunity dialog box or the Opportunity Detail view. Deleting a contact only removes the contact's association with a particular opportunity. The contact is not deleted from the database.

Url.Title: Removing a Product from an Opportunity
Url.Abstract: Removing a Product from an Opportunity You can remove products from an opportunity if a customer is no longer interested in the product, or the products were added by mistake. You can remove products from the Insert Opportunity dialog box or Opportunity Detail view. Removing a product only removes the product's association with a particular opportunity. The product is not deleted from the database.

Url.Title: Editing Opportunity Competitors
Url.Abstract: Editing an Opportunity Competitor After you have added a competitor to an Opportunity, you can edit the competitor information from the Edit Competitor dialog box.

Url.Title: Editing the Sales Potential
Url.Abstract: Editing the Sales Potential The sales potential is the total revenue to be gained by the opportunity. By default, the sales potential is the calculated sum of all of the associated products.

Url.Title: Editing Opportunity Contacts
Url.Abstract: Editing an Opportunity Contact After you have added a contact to an opportunity, you can edit the contact by adding information where needed. You cannot, however, change the contact or the contact's title.

Url.Title: Opportunity Marketing Tab
Url.Abstract: Opportunity Marketing Tab Use the Marketing tab on the Opportunity Detail view to see or add campaigns that are associated with the opportunity.

Url.Title: Opportunity Contacts
Url.Abstract: Use this view to add, edit, or remove contacts associated to an opportunity. How Do I? This view contains the following columns:

Url.Title: Opportunity Snapshot
Url.Abstract: Opportunity Snapshot You can view opportunity value and summary information about the selected opportunity in the Opportunity Snapshot in the top section of the Opportunity Detail view. You can edit the information as needed.

Url.Title: Opportunity Statistics
Url.Abstract: Using Opportunity Statistics You can use Opportunity Statistics to view opportunity information at a glance. You can view opportunity statistics for a group of opportunities, or you can select individual opportunities from the Opportunity List view. You can also export opportunities to Exce.

Url.Title: Summary Tab
Url.Abstract: Summary Tab The Opportunity Summary tab appears on the Opportunity Detail view and displays a list of activities and interactions with the selected opportunity. The Last rows relate to the last activity performed. The Next rows display scheduled follow up activities.

Url.Abstract: Setting Opportunity Options Use the Opportunities tab to specify default settings for any new opportunities that you enter into the Saleslogix Web Client. These options only apply when the current user is logged in to the Saleslogix Web Client.

Url.Title: Opportunity Products

Url.Title: Understanding Multi-Currency
Url.Abstract: Understanding Multi-Currency If your company has Saleslogix users (or prospects) in multiple countries using different currencies, your system administrator can enable multi-currency support. If Multi-Currency is enabled, some Saleslogix views will display information or options specific to your selected currency rate. For example, if you are using the British Pound as your default currency, opportunities will display pricing in pounds.

Url.Title: Updating Opportunity Currency
Url.Abstract: Updating the Opportunity Currency You can use the Opportunity Currency dialog box to change an opportunity's current type and the rate of a specified currency.

Url.Title: Updating Multiple Opportunities
Url.Abstract: Updating Multiple Opportunities You can update multiple opportunities at once using the Update Opportunities dialog box.

Url.Title: Changing Your Saleslogix Connector Server
Url.Abstract: Changing Your Saleslogix Connector Server If you change your server on the Connection tab, your data will be synchronized with the new Saleslogix server. However this should not result in duplicate records.

The DuplicateRecord(s) Found view shows the name, account or company name and e-mail address.

Url.Abstract: Completing Multiple E-mail History Records The Quick Complete dialog box opens when you select multiple e-mails to log to history at once. Use the Quick Complete dialog box to enter history information for multiple e-mail messages or you can choose to log information for each e-mail individually.

Url.Title: Record(s) Not Found
Url.Abstract: Record(s) Not Found The Record(s) Not Found view appears when you are recording an e-mail message from Outlook to Saleslogix history, and the contact or lead e-mail address is not in the Saleslogix database. The Record(s) Not Found view shows the subject, who the e-mail is from, and to whom the e-mail is being sent.

Url.Title: Selecting Record(s) to Log History Items for
Url.Abstract: Selecting Record(s) to Log History Items for If you are using Microsoft Outlook as your e-mail application, you can save Outlook e-mail messages as Saleslogix history items. If you send an e-mail to multiple contacts or leads, you can choose which records should receive the associated history item.

Url.Abstract: Query Builder Statement Operators When you add a conditional statement, you must select an operator. Url.Abstract: Using "Not" in a Conditional Statement You can insert NOT in front of a conditional statement or a group of conditional statements. If NOT is inserted in front of a group of conditional statements, it applies to all conditional statements within that group.

Url.Title: What are Virtual Server-Side Cursors (VSSC)
Url.Abstract: What are Virtual Server-Side Cursors (VSSC) Virtual Server-Side Cursors (VSSC) are designed to improve performance and memory usage for large groups in the Groups and List views in the Saleslogix Client.

Url.Title: Width specifier
Url.Abstract: Width Specifier A width specifier sets the minimum field width for a formatted field. If the minimum field width is not filled, it will be padded with blanks added in front of the value unless a left justification specifier is used.

Url.Title: Adding a Global Join
Url.Abstract: Adding a Global Join A global join is permanent and exists from session to session in the Query Builder data tree structure. Be very careful when creating global joins. You can inadvertently create a global join that causes severe performance problems.

Url.Title: Adding a Local Join
Url.Abstract: Adding a Local Join A local join is temporary and only exists in the Query Builder for one session. The object using the resulting query will hold the properties of this local join while it is in use.

Url.Title: Argument index specifier
Url.Abstract: Argument Index Specifier The argument index specifier sets the current argument list index to a specified value. The first argument's index is 0. This is used to format the same argument multiple times.

Url.Title: Assigning a Query Layout
Url.Abstract: Assigning a Query Layout Use the Assign Query Layout dialog box to specify the appearance of each column of data (or field) in the query.

Url.Title: Calculation Alias
Url.Abstract: Calculation Alias Enter a name to be used in the calculation. It cannot contain any spaces or symbols. When the calculated field is used in constructing a plugin or query, this name is displayed in the list of available fields. This is a required field. You will be unable to finish creating any calculated field unless this has been set.

Url.Title: Types of Calculated Fields
Url.Abstract: Types of Calculated Fields There are two types of calculations: string and numeric. When you build a calculated field using strings (alphanumeric values), you concatenate, or connect, the values together to create one value. Numeric fields cannot be used in a string. When you build a calculated field using one or more numeric fields, you perform a mathematical operation (adding, subtracting, multiplying or dividing) on the values of each field to create a new value. You can also use constants in numeric calculations. Fields that are not numeric (such as strings) cannot be used in numeric calculations.

Url.Title: Caption Alignment
Url.Abstract: Caption Alignment Select an alignment for the labels on each column header. The options are Left, Right, and Center. The default is Left.

Url.Abstract: Cascade Options Related Topics

Url.Title: Select a Condition Value
Url.Abstract: Selecting a Condition Value When you complete the Assign Condition dialog box while setting up a condition in the Query Builder, a Browse button appears next to the Value is box. If you click Browse, the Select Values dialog box displays all of the values in the database for the field you selected. Select a value and click OK.

Url.Title: Data Relationships
Url.Abstract: Data Relationships A relational database contains multiple tables. The structure of the database is defined by how these tables relate to one another. Since data is acquired based on table relationships, it is important to understand the relationship between tables before adding custom tables and fields to the database. It is also helpful when creating queries for lookups, groups, subscription rules or templates, and so on.

Url.Title: Delete a Global Join
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Global Join A global join is permanent and exists from session to session in the Query Builder data tree structure. You cannot delete predefined global joins (system joins).

Url.Title: Edit a Global Join
Url.Abstract: Editing a Global Join A global join is permanent and exists from session to session in the Query Builder data tree structure. With predefined global joins (system joins), you can only edit the Join Type, Visibility, and Cascade Type options.

Url.Title: ID fields in tables
Url.Abstract: ID Fields in Tables Every table has at least one ID field that is used to ensure that each record in the table is unique. When a record is added to the ACCOUNT table, a value is automatically entered in the AccountID field. Each time a record is added, a value is generated based on information in the key file.

Url.Title: Inner joins
Url.Abstract: Inner Joins An inner join is the default type for local joins. Use an inner join to include only records where the values in the fields you are joining are the same in both the Parent and Child tables.

Url.Title: Join Example
Url.Abstract: Join Example The example for Inner, Left, and Right joins use the OPPORTUNITY and ACTIVITY tables to demonstrate each type of join. The OPPORTUNITY and ACTIVITY tables each contain the OPPORTUNITYID field. Opportunities can exist without associated activities. Activities can exist that are not related to an opportunity. Each join example uses the same opportunity and activity records to demonstrate that different types of joins result in different records being selected. The join results records are shown in a separate column in each of the three types of joins.

Url.Title: Join Types
Url.Abstract: Join Types Inner - Include only records where the joined fields from both tables are equal. Example

Url.Title: Left joins
Url.Abstract: Left Joins A left join is the default type for global joins. Use a left join to include all the records in the Parent table that meet the selection criteria and only those records in the Child table where the values in the fields you are joining are equal.

Url.Title: Left justification indicator
Url.Abstract: Left Justification Indicator A left justification indicator is a "-" character that precedes a width specifier. It essentially tells the width to pad any fields shorter than the minimum width after the value instead of the default, before the value.

Url.Title: Operators
Url.Abstract: Operators There are four mathematical operators in calculated fields: add, subtract, multiply, and divide. Use brackets to group parts of your calculations. Only numeric fields (such as integer fields) can be used in numeric calculations. If an operator is used in a string-calculated field, it will act as just another character. Operators in string calculated fields will not perform any operations.

Url.Title: Precision specifier
Url.Abstract: Precision Specifier A precision specifier determines how many decimal places to use in a floating point integer. In Saleslogix, the default precision specifier is 2 decimal places. However, not all field types support unlimited decimal place storage and use accordingly.

Url.Title: Right Joins
Url.Abstract: Right Joins Use a right join to include all the records in the Child table that meet the selection criteria and only those rows in the Parent table where the values in the fields you are joining are equal.

Url.Abstract: Showing a Global Join In Saleslogix, a number of global joins are set up for you. However, not all of them are visible when the Query Builder is opened due to space constraints. Url.Title: Saleslogix Personal Web Server
Url.Abstract: Saleslogix Personal Web Server The Personal Wewww.saleslogix.comb Server hosts the Saleslogix portals on a Remote Client computer.

Url.Title: Understanding the Saleslogix Offline Web Client
Url.Abstract: Understanding the Saleslogix Offline Web Client The Offline Web Client functions like the Saleslogix Remote Client except that users connect to their local database using the Web Client. The Offline Web Client allows you to work offline without an active internet connection.

Url.Title: Subscription and Security
Url.Abstract: Subscription and Security You can use subscription to select, or subscribe to, accounts you use on a regular basis and want to store on your local database. Using subscription minimizes your database size and the time required to synchronize updated information to the main office database. You and your system administrator can establish what accounts you need to subscribe to.

Url.Title: What's New
Url.Abstract: What's New Use What's New to see a list of all recent changes to information you can access. This view presents a list of all new or modified accounts, contacts, leads, opportunities, activities, notes, history, contract, defects and returns. You can only see information your security allows you to access.

Url.Title: What's New for Disconnected Web Users
Url.Abstract: What's New for Offline Web Client Users Use the What's New view to track additions, updates, and deletions to your local database, and to subscribe to accounts. What's New information is organized on a series of tabs.

Url.Title: Understanding Conflict Resolution
Url.Abstract: Understanding Conflict Resolution Saleslogix Network Client and Remote users may both need to make changes to the same record. A Network user’s changes are directly applied to the main office database. Remote users change their local database, and synchronize with the main office, which then applies their changes.

Url.Title: What Is Synchronization?
Url.Abstract: What Is Synchronization? If your company has Remote users who cannot connect to a central computing environment, such as a wide area network or on-line system, the changes they make to their database will be inconsistent with the information in their database and the Host database. Synchronization reconciles these changes, applies changes to the workgroup database, and creates files that remote clients can retrieve to update remote databases.

Url.Title: Adding and Editing Report Conditions
Url.Abstract: Adding and Editing Report Conditions Report conditions enable you to modify the content of a pre-defined report to generate the most useful data. The options available to you will vary depending on the selections that you make.

Url.Title: Job Notifications
Url.Abstract: Job Notifications If a job notification alert appears in the menu bar, the results of a job are ready for you to review. Click the drop-down arrow to display notification details and to access the result of your job. The number next to the icon shows how many jobs are available for you to view.

Url.Title: Jobs Progress Dialog
Url.Abstract: Jobs Progress Dialog If you opted to Run the report in step 2, the progress message box appears. Do one of the following:Wait for the job to complete and open your report from the link that displays.Click Close to dismiss the box. The report continues to process in the background. When the report is available, a job notification alert appears in the menu bar. You can either view the report from the Job Notifications box or from the Reports History tab.

Url.Title: Managing your Scheduled Reports
Url.Abstract: Managing your Scheduled Reports Use the Schedules tab to keep track of reports that you have scheduled. This tab shows the name of the report, the description, start time and end time. The Execution Count column shows the number of times the report has run.

Url.Title: Reports Wizard
Url.Abstract: Report Scheduling Wizard The Report Scheduling Wizard allows you to modify report parameters to adjust the content of the selected report to meet your needs.

Url.Title: Viewing and Printing Detail View Reports
Url.Abstract: Viewing and Printing Detail View Reports Some detail views have a detail report that you can view or print. You can view and print detail reports from the Contact, Account, Opportunity, Sales Order, Ticket, and Defect detail views.

Url.Title: Viewing Report History
Url.Abstract: Viewing, Printing, and Storing Reports When you run a report, it is stored in the Reports History tab until you choose to delete it. From this tab you can see history for the report, open the report, print, save the report elsewhere, or store the report for future reference.

Url.Title: Resource Information Boxes
Url.Abstract: Resource Information Boxes The resource information boxes contain information about the selected resource. You can edit or delete the information as needed.

Url.Title: Using the Resource List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Resource List View The Resources List view displays all of the resources that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Abstract: Using the Defects Tab The Defects tab on the Ticket and Return Detail views displays all associated defects. Use this tab to add or remove an association with a defect.

Use the Lookup to narrow the list of products and packages. After you add a product, you can edit the product details, such as the discount, adjusted price and quantity.

Url.Title: Sales Order Billing and Shipping Tab
Url.Abstract: Sales Order Billing and Shipping Tab The Bill/Ship Address tab appears on the Sales Order Detail View. Use this tab to manage the billing and shipping addresses for a sales order.

Url.Title: Deleting a Sales Order
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Sales Order You can delete a sales order at any time. Deleting a sales order also deletes any associated products and addresses.

Url.Title: Editing Product Information
Url.Abstract: Editing Product Information Use the Edit Sales Order Item dialog box to edit a sales order's product information.

Url.Title: Removing a Product from a Sales Order
Url.Abstract: Removing a Product from a Sales Order You can remove products from a sales order if a customer is no longer interested in the product, or the products were added by mistake. You can remove products from the Insert Sales Order dialog box or Sales Order Detail view. Deleting a product only removes the product's association with a particular sales order. The product is not deleted from the database.

Url.Title: Sales Order Products Tab
Url.Abstract: Sales Order Products Tab Use this view to add, edit, or remove products associated with the sales order.

Url.Title: Editing Sales Order Snapshot Details
Url.Abstract: Editing Sales Order Snapshot Details Use this dialog box to edit the tax rate, shipping or discount of a sales order.

Url.Title: Sales Order Snapshot
Url.Abstract: Sales Order Snapshot You can view information about the selected sales order's value in the Sales Order Snapshot in the top section of the Sales Order Detail view. You can edit the information as needed.

Url.Title: Sales Orders Tab
Url.Abstract: The Sales Orders tab appears in the Account and Opportunity Detail views. You can use the Sales Orders tab to track the sales orders for an account or opportunity. You can add, edit or delete associated sales orders from the Sales Orders tab.

Url.Title: Sales Process Snapshot
Url.Abstract: Sales Process Snapshot The Sales Process Snapshot provides an overview of the status of the process to date. You can view statistics in the Sales Process Snapshot box, located in the upper-right corner of the Sales Processes tab.

Url.Title: Sales Process Tab
Url.Abstract: Sales Process Tab You can use the Sales Processes tab to attach a sales process to an opportunity, change the sales process currently attached to an opportunity, or work on the steps in a sales process.

Url.Title: Actions that Trigger Saleslogix Events
Url.Abstract: Actions that Trigger Events in Saleslogix Related Topics

Url.Title: Using SpeedSearch Filter By Options
Url.Abstract: Using SpeedSearch Filter By Options The Filter By options are made available by clicking Advanced in the SpeedSearch Client. These filters allow you to limit the results to records that meet specific criteria.

Url.Title: Previewing SpeedSearch Results

Url.Title: Viewing SpeedSearch Results
Url.Abstract: Viewing SpeedSearch Results The Results tab displays a list of items matching your search criteria. As you select each item, it appears on the Preview tab. Clicking a link in the Results tab will either take you to the record's detail view, or will open the activity or history details dialog box.

Url.Title: Using the Standard Problem Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Standard Problem Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add or edit information for a selected record.

Url.Title: Standard Problem Information Boxes
Url.Abstract: Standard Problem Information Boxes The standard problem boxes contain information about the selected problem. You can edit or delete the information as needed.

Url.Title: Using the Standard Problem List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Standard Problem List View The Standard Problems List view displays all of the standard problems that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Managing Standard Problems
Url.Abstract: Managing Standard Problems Use this view to enter information that you want to be available to all users when adding tickets.

Url.Title: What Are Standard Problems and Resolutions?
Url.Abstract: What Are Standard Problems and Resolutions? A standard problem is an issue in your product that generates communication from multiple customers. Your call center may frequently receive calls about problems that are similar. Use Standard Problems to record descriptions of these problems, and Standard Resolutions to store proven ways they can be resolved. Once standard problems and resolutions are established, they can be used to supplement a ticket description or used as the ticket resolution.

Url.Title: Standard Problem Standard Resolutions Tab
Url.Abstract: Standard Problem Standard Resolutions Tab Use this view to view or associate standard resolutions with a problem.

Url.Title: Using the Resolution Detail View
Url.Abstract: Using the Resolution Detail View Use the Detail view to see, add, or edit information for a selected record.

Url.Title: Using the Standard Resolutions List View
Url.Abstract: Using the Standard Resolutions List View The Standard Problems List view displays all of the standard problems that you have access to. You can use groups and lookups to narrow the list of records that display.

Url.Title: Adding or Editing a Standard Problem Resolution
Url.Abstract: Adding or Editing a Standard Problem Resolution Standard problem resolutions provide information for resolving a commonly occurring problem.

Url.Title: Standard Resolution Standard Problems Tab
Url.Abstract: Standard Resolution Standard Problems Tab Use this view to view or associate standard problems with a resolution.

Url.Title: Attaching or Removing Template Files
Url.Abstract: Attaching or Removing Template Files You can attach Windows files or Library files to a template. When the template is used in a mail merge, the attached files are automatically sent to the contact or lead. If the template containing the attachment is copied, the attachment is copied also. You can also remove an attachment from a template.

Url.Title: Copying a Template
Url.Abstract: Copying a Template You can copy private and public templates; however, when you copy a public template, it will be saved as a private template.

Url.Title: Creating a Template
Url.Abstract: Creating a Template Using the template editor, you can create a private template. To create a new template

Url.Title: Creating a Proposal
Url.Abstract: Creating a Proposal You can use Mail Merge to create sales proposals. To create a proposal Related Topics

Url.Title: Customizing Insert SLX Field Menu
Url.Abstract: Customizing Insert SLX Field Menu Saleslogix allows you to customize the fields on the Insert SLX Field menu. You can set the format type and string for the field, insert a separator, remove a field, or move a field up or down in the list.

Url.Title: Deleting a Template
Url.Abstract: Deleting a Template You can only delete private templates that you own. However, if the template has been released to others and is shared, your Saleslogix administrator should remove the template.

Url.Title: Deleting Merge Fields
Url.Abstract: Deleting Merge Fields You can remove merge fields from templates from within the E-mail, Letter, or Fax Template Editor.

Url.Title: Editing a Template
Url.Abstract: Editing a Template You can edit private or public templates; you can edit a public template, if you copy the template and save it as a private template.

Url.Title: Editing Columns
Url.Abstract: Editing Columns When editing the columns in the Edit Columns dialog box, the column information must be manually entered based on the SQL used. There is no automatic synchronization between the SQL and the column information. If no column information is provided, the columns will be formatted using the default settings and the field names will be used for the column captions. If more columns are defined than are contained in the SQL, then the extra column information will be discarded. If fewer columns are defined than are contained in the SQL, then the remaining columns will be formatted using the default settings but will have no caption.

Url.Title: Editing Merge Fields
Url.Abstract: Editing Merge Fields You can use the Mail Merge Field Editor to edit new and existing merge fields. You can view the template merge fields in the list view and your edit options in the edit pane. You can also remove merge fields from the template by selecting the Remove From Template button on the toolbar.

Url.Title: Editing SQL
Url.Abstract: Editing SQL You can use the Edit SQL dialog box to create and edit SQL statements for mail merge fields. You can use the Edit menu or toolbar to Cut, Copy, Paste, or Delete text. You can also insert parameters into an SQL statement.

Url.Title: Editing SQL Image Fields
Url.Abstract: Editing SQL Image Fields You can use the Mail Merge Field Editor to edit new and existing SQL Image merge fields. When you select an SQL Image field from the list view, the edit options will display in the edit pane.

Url.Title: Editing SQL Text Fields
Url.Abstract: Editing SQL Text Fields You can use the Mail Merge Field Editor to edit new and existing SQL Text merge fields. When you select an SQL Text field from the list view, the edit options will display in the edit pane.

Url.Title: Email Options
Url.Abstract: Email Options When creating an e-mail template, you can set options for the e-mail message(s) you want to send. For example, as the administrator, you may need to send out a mass e-mail on behalf of your sales team from a generic company address (i.e., salesteam@company.com). You can have the Reply To field in the outbound e-mail populated dynamically during the mail merge so that when recipients reply to the e-mail they have received, it is automatically addressed to their assigned account manager.

Url.Title: Inserting Special Fields
Url.Abstract: Inserting Special Fields You can click the Insert Special Field button of the E-mail, Fax, or Letter Template Editor to insert a new opportunity product table, SQL statement, or custom mail merge field.

Url.Title: Managing and Selecting Templates
Url.Abstract: Managing and Selecting Templates You can use the Manage Templates or Select a Template dialog box to access the Public and Private templates that are available to you.

Url.Title: Setting Merge Field Format
Url.Abstract: Setting Merge Field Format Use the Format Saleslogix Field dialog box to set the format type and format string for a Saleslogix merge field.

Url.Title: Setting or Updating the Properties for a Template
Url.Abstract: Setting or Updating the Properties for a Template You can set or update the properties for a private or public template when creating, editing, or copying a template. If you are editing or copying a template, some property settings will default to the settings for the selected template; however, you can change these settings if desired.

Url.Title: Using Saleslogix Merge Fields
Url.Abstract: Using Saleslogix Merge Fields The Insert SLX Field menu contains the most commonly used Saleslogix merge fields. However, when creating or editing a template, if you need aSaleslogix field that is not in the menu, you can use select More SLX Fields to access all the Saleslogix merge fields. In addition, you can add a field to the menu, and customize the menu.

Url.Title: Using the E-mail Editor
Url.Abstract: Using the E-mail Editor With the E-mail Editor window you can create a new e-mail template or edit an existingtemplate. Like the Letter and Fax Editors, the E-mail Editor contains a Saleslogix toolbar which give you access to the special template functions as well as many Microsoft Word features.

Url.Title: Using the Fax Editor
Url.Abstract: Using the Fax Editor With the Fax Editor window you can create a new Fax template or edit an existing template. Like the E-Mail and Letter Editors, the Fax Editor contains a Saleslogix toolbar which give you access to the special template functions as well as many Microsoft Word features.

Url.Title: Using the Letter Editor
Url.Abstract: Using the Letter Editor With the E-mail Editor window you can create a new Letter template or edit an existing template. Like the E-mail and Fax Editors, the Letter Editor contains a Saleslogix toolbar which give you access to the special template functions as well as many Microsoft Word features.

Url.Title: Using the Template Editor
Url.Abstract: Using the Template Editor With the Template Editor, you can create a new template or edit an existing template. The editor contains a Saleslogix toolbar which gives you access to the special template functions as well as many Microsoft Word features. The features available depend on whether the type of template you are editing is a Letter, an E-mail or a Fax.

Url.Title: Adding and Editing Ticket Activities
Url.Abstract: Adding and Editing Ticket Activities Use this view to add a new activity for work done on the ticket or to edit/update an existing activity. Ticket Activities enable you to track the time, the types of tasks, and any associated costs involved in resolving a ticket. Activities are recorded by activity type and charge rate and are used for billing the customer against their service contracts.You can set up future (follow-up) activities for yourself or another user.

Url.Title: Account Service Information
Url.Abstract: Account Service Information The Account Service Information dialog box provides account, ticket, contact, asset, and contract information to help you understand the relationship of the person requesting assistance to his or her account. You can also use this dialog box to determine the type of assistance you can provide according to the account's service contract.

Url.Abstract: Using the Returns Tab The Returns tab on the Account and Ticket Detail views lists all returns for the selected record.

Url.Title: Sending an E-mail Message from a Ticket
Url.Abstract: Sending an E-mail Message from a Ticket You can send an e-mail message to a customer or another Saleslogix user while adding a new ticket or from the Ticket Detail view. The e-mail can provide ticket information; to inform others including the customer that you opened the ticket, or to ask questions to help resolve the issue.

Url.Title: Using the Defects Tab
Url.Abstract: Using the Defects Tab The Defects tab on the Ticket and Return Detail views displays all associated defects. Use this tab to add or remove an association with a defect.

Url.Title: Using the Ticket Activities Tab
Url.Abstract:
Using the Ticket Activities Tab The Ticket Activities tab shows all activities associated with working on and resolving the ticket. Use the Ticket Activities tab to add a new activity for work done on the ticket or to edit/update an existing activity. You can set up future (follow-up) activities for yourself or another user.
You can click a column heading to sort the list according to that column. By default, the newest Ticket Activity (according to date and time) appears at the top of the list.

Url.Title: Ticket Comments Tab
Url.Abstract: Using the Ticket Comments Tab Use the Comments text box for all internal notes, troubleshooting steps, or other important information related to the ticket.

Url.Title: Ticket Details Tab
Url.Abstract: Ticket Detail View Details Tab The Ticket Details tab contains the Subject, problem Description, and problem Resolution text boxes. Use these boxes when describing the problem and how it was resolved.

Url.Title: Ticket Journal Tab
Url.Abstract: Using the Ticket Journal Tab The Journal tab contains a historical log of actions, such as changes made to information boxes for a ticket. The system automatically posts some of the information in the Journal boxes on the tab; users cannot change that information. A customer service user or manager can use the Journal tab to track and measure customer response time and effort.

Url.Title: Ticket Related Assets Tab
Url.Abstract: Using the Ticket Related Assets Tab Use the Related Assets tab on the Ticket Detail view to see all assets associated with the selected ticket and to associate and disassociate other related assets to the ticket.

Url.Title: Using Punch In and Punch Out
Url.Abstract: Using Punch In and Punch Out The Punch In and Punch Out function enables you to track the time spent assisting a customer for each ticket. When you click the Punch In button on a ticket's detail view, Saleslogix begins timing the activity. When you are finished, you can click Punch Out. Saleslogix stops timing the activity and adds an activity record to the Ticket Activities tab for the ticket.

Url.Abstract: I Cannot Delete a User Error message: Other users report to this user. This user cannot be deleted. Solution: Clear the User is a Manager check box in the User Detail view of the user you want to delete.

Url.Title: Why Can I Not Move this Contact?
Url.Abstract: Why Can I Not Move this Contact? You cannot move the last contact of an account if there are any open records that cannot move with the contact. These records include, attachments, literature requests, opportunities, sales orders, tickets, returns, and contracts.
